## D021: Per-Card Unique Visuals — Homepage + Section Indexes
**Date**: 2026-03-02
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: Homepage path-cards and section index cards showed only text (h3 + p).
Each card lacked visual differentiation — visitors encountered a uniform wall of text
cards across the homepage and every section index. The five path-cards each represent
fundamentally different content types (covenant articles, historical gap, analytical
connection, empirical evidence, advocacy toolkit) yet appeared visually identical.

**Decision**: Add a `.card-visual` CSS pattern in `base.css` with type variants
(stat, bar, figure, cta). Each homepage path-card gains a unique visual element
above its title. Section index cards (connection, evidence, gap, action) gain
stat callouts. Covenant and educator indexes skipped — already visually differentiated.

Homepage visuals:
- Covenant: stat — "10 Articles"
- Gap: stat — "49 Years Unratified"
- Connection: bar — 80% fill (20/25 Composite Score)
- Evidence: figure — "$527B AI Capex 2026"
- Action: cta — "Contact Your Senators →"

Section index visuals:
- Connection: dynamic `relatedArticles.length` count per card
- Evidence: "$990B Medicaid Cuts" + "5 Surviving Hypotheses"
- Gap: "49 Years" / "5 Core Objections" / "5 Rebuttals" / "3 Misconceptions" / "173 Ratifying Nations"
- Action: "49 Years Overdue" / "4 Steps" / "7 Key Points" / "3 Templates" / "3 Lessons"

**Reasoning**:
- Pure HTML + CSS — zero JavaScript, zero new components, renders at build time
- CSS classes in `base.css` shared across all index pages (DRY)
- Visual type varies by content nature — stat for counts, bar for scores, figure for
  currency amounts, cta for action prompts
- Section index stats use lookup maps keyed by page slug — maintainable, explicit
- Connection index uses dynamic `relatedArticles.length` — stays accurate as content evolves
- Covenant index already has `.card-number` + pivotal badges; educator index has
  level/duration/type badges — additional stats would add noise, not signal

**What follows**:
- Homepage immediately more scannable — visitors perceive five distinct content types
- Section indexes gain preview information that aids navigation decisions
- Pattern extensible: any future section index can add stats via the same CSS classes
- All labels use noun phrases — no E-prime violations

