## D031: Six-Agent Content Audit + Fact-Check Corrections
**Date**: 2026-03-03
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: Six parallel agents audited all 45 pages of content against authoritative sources. Found 14 verified errors, 20 warnings, and 15+ informational items. Key findings:
- 1979 SFRC hearings on ICESCR had occurred (site claimed "no hearing")
- 9 administrations, not 13 (direct count: Carter through Trump 2nd)
- SCOTUS struck down IEEPA tariffs Feb 20, 2026 (site had pre-SCOTUS figures)
- Multiple attribution errors (Tax Foundation vs. Yale Budget Lab, Faros 75% recharacterization)
- NATO membership count outdated (31→32, Sweden joined March 2024)

**Decision**: Fix all 14 errors and 20 warnings using additive approach — preserve existing facts as "before" context where pedagogically valuable, then add corrected figures. Add authoritative acronym linking (ICESCR→OHCHR, ICCPR→OHCHR, UDHR→UN, CESCR→OHCHR) on first mention per page across ~40 files.

**Key corrections**:
- Timeline: added 1979 SFRC hearings, corrected admin count to 9, added Carter CEDAW signing
- Tariffs: restructured as pre-SCOTUS → SCOTUS ruling → post-SCOTUS Section 122 regime
- ICCPR ratification: "unanimous consent" → "division vote" (138 Cong. Rec. S4781-S4783)
- ICCPR death penalty: "general prohibition" → Article 6 restricts but permits for most serious crimes
- Faros: "75% of organizations saw no gains" → "75% of engineers use AI tools, yet most organizations report no measurable productivity gains"
- $990B Medicaid: qualified as "$990B gross (~$911B net)" throughout
- Deloitte: two-tier (34/37) → three-tier (34% deep, 30% limited, 37% non-adoption)
- Four Scarcities: standardized on "curation" (user rejected rename to "attention")

**What follows**:
- HN-curation connection documented in glossary (Observatory + Curation Scarcity entries)
- All treaty acronyms link to authoritative sources on first mention per page
- Blog spec includes same acronym-linking convention for agent-authored posts

---

## D032: WCAG AA Color-Contrast Fix — Global --color-text-muted Strengthening
**Date**: 2026-03-03
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: Automated axe-core accessibility audit (via Playwright) flagged 227 color-contrast violations across all 8 representative pages. Root cause: `--color-text-muted` failed WCAG AA 4.5:1 minimum contrast ratio on both page backgrounds (`--color-bg`) and card surfaces (`--color-surface`) in both light and dark themes.

- Light mode: `#78909c` on `#fafafa` → ~2.92:1 (requires 4.5:1)
- Dark mode: `#5b7279` on `#002d38` → ~3.65:1 (requires 4.5:1)

Affected elements: lens/theme toggle buttons, breadcrumb links, breadcrumb text, map legend items, meta text, table captions.

**Decision**: Two-layer fix:
1. Strengthen `--color-text-muted` globally (light: `#78909c` → `#546e7a`, dark: `#5b7279` → `#7e9aa3`) — passes AA on `--color-bg`
2. Add `--color-toggle-inactive` for buttons sitting on `--color-surface` (light: `#546e7a`, dark: `#99b0b8`) — passes AA on the brighter surface background

**Verified contrast ratios**:
- Light muted on bg: `#546e7a` on `#fafafa` → 4.59:1
- Light toggle on surface: `#546e7a` on `#ffffff` → 4.79:1
- Dark muted on bg: `#7e9aa3` on `#002d38` → 5.60:1
- Dark toggle on surface: `#99b0b8` on `#093946` → 4.85:1

**Reasoning**:
- Muted text still looks muted — darker in light mode, slightly brighter in dark mode — but now meets minimum readability standards
- Two-variable approach acknowledges that breadcrumbs (on page bg) and buttons (on card surfaces) sit on different backgrounds with different contrast requirements
- Global fix covers all elements using `--color-text-muted`, not just the flagged ones

**Files modified**: `src/styles/base.css` (4 lines: 2 variable definitions per theme), `src/styles/lens.css` (2 lines: toggle button color references)

**What follows**:
- Re-audit: 0 violations across 8 representative pages (axe-core, WCAG 2A + 2AA + best-practice)
- Any future CSS additions using `--color-text-muted` automatically meet contrast requirements
- Blog inherits the fix via `@main` alias (shared base.css)

