## D033: Glossary External Sources + Validation
**Date**: 2026-03-03
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: The glossary (49 terms, 8 categories) contained only internal `seeAlso` links. No authoritative external sources linked definitions to the institutions, academic literature, or legislative bodies that originate the concepts. This left definitions unverifiable and the semantic web layer (JSON-LD, SKOS) without outbound authority connections.

**Decision**: Add an `ExternalSource` interface with four authority levels (`primary`, `academic`, `reference`, `literary`) to the glossary data model. Populate 19 terms with 25 source entries. Validate all definitions against their sources, correcting five substantive findings via discriminator evaluation.

**Data model additions**:
- `AuthorityLevel` type: `'primary' | 'academic' | 'reference' | 'literary'`
- `ExternalSource` interface: `{ url, label, authority }`
- Optional `sources?: ExternalSource[]` on `GlossaryTerm`

**Authority level → semantic web mapping**:
- `primary` → `schema:sameAs` + `skos:exactMatch` (definitive institutional source)
- `academic` → `schema:isBasedOn` + `skos:closeMatch` (scholarly/encyclopedic)
- `reference` → `schema:isBasedOn` + `rdfs:seeAlso` (originating organization)
- `literary` → `schema:isBasedOn` + `rdfs:seeAlso` (cultural origin)

**Source coverage**: 19 of 49 terms received external sources; 30 remain project-specific (hypotheses, paths, scarcities, internal frameworks) with no external authority to cite.

**Validation findings** (0 critical, 8 warnings, 9 informational):
- `ratification`: "67-vote supermajority" corrected → "two-thirds of Senators present" (Constitution Article II, Section 2)
- `senate-consent`: "two-thirds Senate supermajority" corrected → "two-thirds of Senators present" (internal consistency)
- `article-15-science`: "guarantees" corrected → "recognizes" (ICESCR treaty language)
- `escr`: Positive/negative binary replaced with synthesized definition acknowledging historical framing + OHCHR's tripartite correction; cultural rights added (discriminator: C wins 22/25)
- `jevons-effect`: "cost reduction" corrected → "efficiency improvements that reduce effective cost" (Wikipedia/Jevons original)
- `lapp`: Pivot/Perspective descriptions aligned with Braver Angels source descriptions
- All intentional reinterpretations (bifurcation, constraint-removal, fair-witness, ADA pattern, differential-diagnosis) documented as acceptable

**Observatory-blog sync evaluation**: Manual review (D, 20/25) recommended as primary approach; build-time hash comparison (A, 19/25) as automated backstop when blog grows past ~20 posts. Git-based webhooks (C, 16/25) eliminated for complexity. Not implemented — evaluation only.

**Rendering**: "Sources:" line in glossary `<details>` block with external links and ↗ indicator.

**Files modified**: `src/data/glossary.ts` (interface + 19 terms), `src/pages/glossary.astro` (rendering), `src/pages/.well-known/glossary.json.ts` (sameAs/isBasedOn), `src/pages/.well-known/taxonomy.json.ts` (exactMatch/closeMatch/seeAlso), `src/pages/.well-known/agent-inbox.json.ts` (blog RSS endpoint + term count)

**What follows**:
- Glossary page renders "Sources:" with working external links for 19 terms
- JSON-LD glossary includes `sameAs` (10 terms) and `isBasedOn` (12 terms)
- SKOS taxonomy includes `exactMatch` (10), `closeMatch` (5), `rdfs:seeAlso` (external, 7)
- Agent-inbox advertises blog RSS for single-hop observatory discovery
- Future source additions follow the same ExternalSource pattern

## D034: Landing Page Strategy — Persona Pages Before Emotional Hook
**Date**: 2026-03-03
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: The site had one entry point (homepage) serving all audiences. Social traffic from the Bluesky soft launch arrives without context. Two approaches competed: (A) build a generic emotional `/why` page first, or (B) build five persona-specific landing pages (`/for/voters`, `/for/politicians`, `/for/educators`, `/for/researchers`, `/for/developers`) first.

**Decision**: Build all three tiers, persona pages as primary. Discriminator scored B at 21/25 (rising) vs A at 17→15/25 (declining). `/why` and `/start` remain active TODOs as complementary upstream pages.

**Reasoning**: The five-lens model (D017) already permeates the entire codebase — lensFraming frontmatter, LensToggle, persona-specific content on every page. Persona landing pages complete this architecture at the entry point. Each page sets `defaultLens`, speaks the audience's language from the first sentence, and routes to relevant sections without requiring visitors to discover the lens toggle. The Bluesky strategy maps naturally to persona-specific URLs (voter posts → `/for/voters`, methodology posts → `/for/researchers`). Generic `/why` partially duplicates existing `/action/why-act`.

**Key finding**: Chain integrity distinguished the candidates. `/why` → homepage leaves a routing gap (which persona content?). `/for/voters` → `/action` completes without gaps. Each persona URL also generates a distinct measurable signal for analytics.

**Visitor funnel**: `/why` (convince) → `/start` (orient) → `/for/X` (personalize) → deep content.

**Build order**: voters → politicians → educators → researchers → developers (matches marketing pipeline sequencing).

**What follows**:
- Five `/for/*` pages using existing lensFraming copy and marketing messaging
- `/why` and `/start` follow as upstream complementary pages
- Each persona URL becomes a shareable, testable entry point for targeted outreach

## D035: Rocket Loader Disabled — Cloudflare Script Rewriting Breaks Astro Islands
**Date**: 2026-03-03
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: iPhone users reported blank screens on unratified.org. Diagnostic investigation revealed Cloudflare Rocket Loader rewrites every `<script>` tag to a custom MIME type, deferring execution to its own async loader. This breaks Astro's island hydration system (`astro-island` custom element), the blocking theme-detection script (designed to run synchronously before render), and `client:load`/`client:visible` registrations. When Rocket Loader fails (content blocker, network timing, specific WebKit builds), no scripts execute — blank screen.

**Decision**: Disable Rocket Loader in Cloudflare Dashboard. No code changes required.

**Reasoning**: Rocket Loader provides marginal performance gains for sites with heavy synchronous JavaScript. Astro static sites already minimize JS — only Svelte islands load client-side, and Astro handles their loading optimally. Rocket Loader's script rewriting actively interferes with Astro's architecture. The tradeoff (theoretical performance gain vs. broken rendering for a subset of users) clearly favors disabling.

**What follows**:
- Scripts execute natively as Astro intended
- Theme-detection runs synchronously before render (no FOUC)
- Island hydration proceeds without Rocket Loader intermediation
- iPhone blank screen reports should cease

---

## D036: Non-Render-Blocking Google Fonts — iOS Blank Screen Fix
**Date**: 2026-03-04
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: After disabling Rocket Loader (D035), a user reported that the "Why the Open Web Matters" blog post still loaded a blank screen on iOS. Investigation confirmed: no Rocket Loader injection, correct CSP headers, valid HTML structure, and content served correctly when fetched. The blog's `<link rel="stylesheet" href="fonts.googleapis.com/...">` tag blocks rendering — if the Google Fonts CDN responds slowly on iOS (network conditions, CDN edge selection, or DNS resolution delay), the entire page remains white until the CSS arrives. No eval/Function calls in the Svelte runtime. No CSP violations. The render-blocking font stylesheet represents the remaining single point of failure for first-paint.

**Decision**: Convert the Google Fonts stylesheet from render-blocking to non-render-blocking using the `media="print" onload="this.media='all'"` pattern in both `BaseLayout.astro` (main site) and `BlogLayout.astro` (blog). Include `<noscript>` fallback for no-JS environments.

**Pattern**:
```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="...fonts..." media="print" onload="this.media='all'" />
<noscript><link rel="stylesheet" href="...fonts..." /></noscript>
```

**Reasoning**:
- Browser treats `media="print"` as low-priority (not render-blocking)
- Once the CSS downloads, `onload` handler switches to `media="all"` — fonts apply
- Page content renders immediately with system monospace fallback (brief FOUT)
- FOUT (Flash of Unstyled Text) vastly preferable to blank screen
- `'unsafe-inline'` in CSP `script-src` covers the `onload` attribute
- `<noscript>` fallback preserves font loading for no-JS users
- Font stack already includes system fallbacks: `"Fira Code", "Cascadia Code", "JetBrains Mono", monospace`

**Files modified**: `src/layouts/BaseLayout.astro`, `blog/src/layouts/BlogLayout.astro`

**What follows**:
- Pages render immediately on all devices regardless of Google Fonts CDN performance
- Brief FOUT visible on slow connections (system monospace → Fira Code swap)
- Combined with D035 (Rocket Loader disabled), eliminates both known causes of iOS blank screen
- Future consideration: self-host Fira Code to eliminate external font dependency entirely

---

## D037: Site Monitor Worker — Cloudflare Worker with Cron Triggers
**Date**: 2026-03-04
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: Three sites now operate in production (unratified.org, blog.unratified.org, observatory.unratified.org) with no automated health monitoring. Failures would go unnoticed until manual discovery. The project already uses Cloudflare infrastructure (Pages, DNS), making a Cloudflare Worker the natural monitoring choice — free tier, same ecosystem, cron trigger support.

**Decision**: Build a Cloudflare Worker (`workers/monitor/`) with four cron triggers: health checks every 5 minutes (HTTP status + response time), content integrity every hour (expected text present on pages), sitemap page count regression daily at 6 AM UTC, and analytics snapshots every 6 hours (deferred until CF API credentials available). Store time-series data in D1. Send email alerts via Resend API with 4-hour cooldown deduplication. Expose `/status` JSON endpoint.

**Architecture**:
- `workers/monitor/src/index.ts` — scheduled + fetch handler routing by cron pattern
- `workers/monitor/src/checks/` — health.ts, content.ts, sitemap.ts
- `workers/monitor/src/alerts/email.ts` — Resend integration with cooldown
- `workers/monitor/src/analytics/snapshot.ts` — stub (deferred)
- `workers/monitor/src/db/` — D1 schema (4 tables) + query helpers
- `workers/monitor/src/status.ts` — public health summary

**Reasoning**:
- Cloudflare Worker cron: free, zero infrastructure, already in ecosystem
- D1 over KV: relational queries needed for time-series health data and alert deduplication
- Resend over native Cloudflare: simpler API, free tier sufficient (3,000/mo), branded emails
- Four cron frequencies: match monitoring urgency (health > content > analytics > sitemap)
- Alert cooldown (4 hours): prevents alert storms during sustained outages
- Graceful degradation: each feature works independently when secrets not configured

**Deferred**:
- Analytics snapshot (needs CF_API_TOKEN + CF_ACCOUNT_ID)
- Analytics dashboard page (src/pages/analytics.astro — needs site tags)
- Deployment (needs D1 database creation + `wrangler secret put` for RESEND_API_KEY)

**What follows**:
- Worker code complete and type-checks cleanly
- Deploy when Cloudflare API credentials and Resend API key available
- Analytics page becomes feasible once snapshot cron populates D1 data

---

## D038: Explicit AI Attribution — "Built by Claude" Across All Touchpoints
**Date**: 2026-03-04
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: The site attributed Claude as "Analysis by Claude (Anthropic)" in the footer and secondary pages — understating reality. Claude generated the entire site: analysis, copy, code, components, design, and blog posts. The homepage contained zero AI disclosure above the fold. JSON-LD structured data and machine-readable endpoints declared no AI authorship. Multiple emerging standards address AI content identification but none has achieved universal adoption for web text content.

**Decision**: Make AI generation explicit everywhere. Change "Analysis by" → "Built by" across all footers. Add above-fold AI disclosure on homepage. Declare Claude as creator in JSON-LD structured data (Schema.org `SoftwareApplication`) and agent-inbox.json. Update copy on about, colophon, start, and for/developers pages. Add per-post AI disclosure in blog post footer. Adopt the WHATWG-proposed `<meta name="ai-generated" content="all">` meta tag on both site layouts.

**Standards landscape**:
- C2PA Content Credentials (mature, media-focused — images/video/audio)
- IPTC Photo Metadata 2025.1 (AI System Used, DigitalSourceType — image-focused)
- WHATWG HTML Issue #9479 (`<meta name="ai-generated">` — proposed, awaiting implementer interest)
- AI Content Metatag Standard v1.1 (community-driven, not standards-body-backed)
- EU AI Act Article 50 (machine-readable AI text marking required by August 2026)
- Schema.org CreativeWork + creator (JSON-LD — Google-recommended format)

**Reasoning**:
- "Built" encompasses code + copy + analysis + design; "Analysis" implied only data work
- Homepage disclosure reaches first-time visitors who never navigate to /about
- JSON-LD `creator` with `SoftwareApplication` type uses existing Schema.org vocabulary Google recommends
- `ai-generated` meta tag costs nothing and positions ahead of EU AI Act mandate
- Matter-of-fact tone: disclosure as feature, not disclaimer
- E-prime compliant throughout

**Files modified** (10 + 2 meta tag):
- `src/layouts/BaseLayout.astro` — footer, JSON-LD creator, ai-generated meta tag
- `blog/src/layouts/BlogLayout.astro` — footer, JSON-LD creator, ai-generated meta tag
- `src/pages/index.astro` — homepage above-fold disclosure
- `src/pages/about/index.astro` — meta-layer section, badge label, vendor note
- `src/pages/colophon.astro` — vendor card heading + copy
- `src/pages/start.astro` — methodology note
- `src/pages/for/developers.astro` — vendor triad description
- `blog/src/layouts/PostLayout.astro` — per-post AI disclosure
- `src/pages/.well-known/agent-inbox.json.ts` — creator + aiGenerated
- `blog/src/pages/.well-known/agent-inbox.json.ts` — creator + aiGenerated

**What follows**:
- Every page on both sites now declares AI generation through visible copy, structured data, and meta tag
- When EU AI Act Article 50 technical standard finalizes (expected May–June 2026), evaluate compliance and adopt if different from current implementation
- Monitor WHATWG issue #9479 for browser-level support of the ai-generated meta tag

