## D073: Bidirectional git-PR Transport for Interagent ACKs
**Date**: 2026-03-06
**Status**: DECIDED + IMPLEMENTED

**Observation**: All outbound `to-{agent}-{NNN}.json` messages were committed to our own `transport/sessions/` but never formally delivered to the peer agent's repo. Peer agents must watch our repo to discover them — passive, not active transport.

**Decision**: Every outbound ACK also travels to the peer agent's repo as a PR. Branch naming: `unratified-agent/{session-id}/{turn-descriptor}`. Message file: `from-unratified-agent-{NNN}.json` with `_note` field pointing to our canonical copy. PR body summarizes; JSON file carries the full interagent/v1 payload.

**Reasoning**: git-PR transport is symmetric by design. The observatory and psychology-agent both send PRs to us; we should send PRs to them. This makes the transport bidirectional and auditable on both sides.

**What follows**: observatory PR #3 sent (`unratified-agent/icescr-framing/mapping-review-001`). Peer repo cloned at `/Users/kashif/Projects/observatory-sqlab`. Pattern codified in /syncinteragent skill Phase 5b.

---

## D074: Semantic Interagent Session Naming Convention
**Date**: 2026-03-06
**Status**: DECIDED

**Observation**: Psychology-agent and observatory use item-based session names (`item2-derivation`, `item4-derivation`) that require context to decode. Our own sessions have used semantic names (`mesh-init`, `icescr-framing`) since inception.

**Decision**: Enforce semantic naming on all unratified-agent sessions and branch names. Never use item-based IDs (`item2`, `item4`, `session-21`). When peer agents use item-based names in their own repos, accept their convention there but use semantic names on our side and note the preference in ACKs.

**Reasoning**: Semantic names make the transport directory self-documenting. Any agent reading `transport/sessions/` understands the exchange without opening files.

**What follows**: Rule documented in /syncinteragent skill Session Naming Convention section. Preference to be communicated to peer agents when opportunity arises in an ACK.

